**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**
How can large language models (LLMs) be integrated into autonomous driving systems to enhance decision-making and reasoning capabilities?

**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**
Solving this problem is crucial for advancing the field of autonomous driving by enabling systems to make more informed and human-like decisions. This research will have significant implications for the safety and reliability of autonomous vehicles, paving the way for more sophisticated algorithms in this rapidly evolving field.

**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**
Integrating LLMs into autonomous driving systems is challenging due to the need for models that can understand and interpret complex driving scenarios in a human-like manner. Additionally, there are technical and computational challenges in scaling and efficiently deploying large models on consumer-grade hardware.

**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**
Previous research has focused on the development of LLMs and their integration into various applications, but there is a gap in how these models can be effectively used in autonomous driving systems. The challenge lies in creating models that can understand and interpret driving scenarios in a human-like manner while being scalable and efficient.

**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**
The proposed methodology involves developing a framework that integrates LLMs into autonomous driving systems using the GLM architecture. The framework will leverage a rule-based motion planner and a text encoder to translate driving scenarios into natural language, allowing a large language model (LLM) to make informed driving decisions. The research will also involve developing new evaluation metrics to assess the reasoning capabilities of LLMs in real-world scenarios. The expected outcomes include a more sophisticated and human-like decision-making framework for autonomous driving systems, as well as advanced evaluation metrics for assessing the performance of LLMs in this domain.

