ruction tuning.\n\n- **Identify gaps and how the project addresses them:**\n  - **Gaps:** Lack of scalable LLMs for AD, insufficient fine-tuning methods for AD-specific tasks.\n  - **Addressing Gaps:** Develop smaller models and advanced fine-tuning techniques.\n\n### 3. Detailed Evaluation Metrics\n- **Define specific evaluation metrics:**\n  - **Safety Metrics:** Collision avoidance rate, emergency braking response time.\n  - **Performance Metrics:** Average driving speed, lane keeping accuracy.\n  - **Adaptability Metrics:** Handling of dynamic traffic conditions, response to unexpected obstacles.\n\n### 4. Integration with Existing Work\n- **Articulate how this research builds upon existing work:**\n  - **DualAD Framework:** Enhance decision-making by integrating smaller, more efficient LLMs.\n  - **Multi-Agent Simulation Platform:** Use the platform to evaluate the performance of integrated LLMs in complex scenarios.\n\n### 5. Timeline and Milestones\n- **Refine the timeline:**\n  - **Month 1-2:** Literature review and methodology development.\n  - **Month 3-4:** Model development and fine-tuning.\n  - **Month 5-6:** Integration and evaluation.\n  - **Month 7:** Final evaluation and reporting.\n\n- **Ensure the timeline is realistic and achievable:**\n  - Allocate sufficient time for each phase.\n  - Include buffer periods for unforeseen challenges.\n\n### 6. Ethical Considerations\n- **Address ethical considerations:**\n  - **Safety:** Ensure models are thoroughly tested to prevent accidents.\n  - **Privacy:** Protect data used in training and simulation.\n\n### 7. Budget and Resources\n- **Outline the budget and resources required:**\n  - **Hardware:** GPUs for model training, simulation hardware.\n  - **Software:** Simulation software, development tools.\n  - **Personnel:** Researchers, data scientists.\n\n- **Identify potential funding sources and partnerships:**\n  - **Funding Sources:** Grants, sponsorships from automotive companies.\n  - **Partnerships:** Collaborations with universities, research institutions.\n\n### 8. Dissemination Plan\n- **Develop a plan for disseminating the research findings:**\n  - **Publications:** Submit papers to conferences and journals.\n  - **Presentations:** Attend industry conferences and workshops.\n  - **Open-Source Contributions:** Share code and datasets on platforms like GitHub.\n\n### 9. Feedback and Review\n- **Seek feedback from peers and mentors:**\n  - Conduct peer reviews.\n  - Present drafts to mentors for feedback.\n\n- **Make necessary revisions based on feedback:**\n  - Incorporate suggestions to improve clarity and comprehensiveness.\n\n### 10. Final Submission\n- **Prepare the final version of the research proposal:**\n  - Ensure all sections are well-organized and coherent.\n  - Review for grammar and spelling errors.\n\n- **Ensure all sections are well-organized and coherent:**\n  - Use clear headings and subheadings.\n  - Provide detailed explanations and justifications.\n\nBy following these steps, the research proposal will be refined and finalized to ensure it is clear, comprehensive, and aligned with the research goals and existing work.\n'}], 'summary': '```json\n{\n  "[Question 1] - What is the problem?": "How can we enhance the efficiency and performance of large language models (LLMs) for real-time applications, such as autonomous driving, while maintaining high accuracy and reducing computational requirements?",\n\n  "[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?": "Solving this problem is crucial for advancing the practical deployment of LLMs in real-time systems like autonomous driving. Efficient LLMs can improve decision-making capabilities, enhance safety, and reduce operational costs. This research will contribute to the broader field of machine learning by providing methodologies that can be applied to other resource-constrained environments, leading to more widespread adoption of LLMs in various industries.",\n\n  "[Question 3] - Why is it hard?": "The challenge lies in balancing model size, performance, and computational efficiency. Naive approaches, such as simply reducing the number of parameters, may lead to significant performance degradation. Technical obstacles include maintaining accuracy after quantization, designing efficient architectures, and effectively fine-tuning models with reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF). Theoretical challenges involve understanding the trade-offs between model complexity and performance in real-time applications.",\n\n  "[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?": "Previous research has focused on scaling up LLMs to improve performance, but there has been limited work on optimizing them for real-time applications with strict computational constraints. Existing solutions often prioritize performance over efficiency, leading to models that are too large for practical deployment. Our approach addresses these gaps by focusing on efficient quantization techniques, smaller architectures, and advanced fine-tuning methods.",\n\n  "[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?": "The proposed methodology includes using post-training quantization methods (dynamic and static quantization) to reduce model size, designing a smaller transformer-based architecture, implementing instruction tuning with PPO, and using RLHF with simulated environments for fine-tuning. The model will be trained and aligned using the Extro-Spective Prediction (ESP) dataset and evaluated using metrics such as clamped temporal error (CTE). Expected outcomes include a smaller, more efficient LLM that maintains high performance for autonomous driving applications."\n}\n```', 'continue_simulation': True, 'communications': ['In Session 0cc677ae-69d2-42e1-b740-bbde06f76164 \nFrom agent2 to agent3: Dear agent3,\n\nI hope this message finds you well. I am currently working on a research proposal that focuses on integrating large language models (LLMs) into autono